%I A394795 #45 Jun 17 2026 18:46:01
%S A394795 1,2,6,12,14,18,20,30,42,60,84,86,90,108,120,126,210,252,264,288,344,
%T A394795 372,422,450,480,990,1580,1650,2870,3648,3996,4400,5166,5544,15198,
%U A394795 15210,15680,18876,19980,22560,23276,30954
%N A394795 Integers k such that 2^d*3^(k/d) is the average of twin prime pairs for some d.
%C A394795 From _Amiram Eldar_, Jun 11 2026: (Start)
%C A394795 A386730(n)*A385433(n) is a term for n >= 2.
%C A394795 All the terms above 1 are even since numbers of the form 2^k * 3^m where k and m are both odd cannot be the average of twin prime pairs, unless k = m = 1. Write k = 2*k'+1, m = 2*m'+1, and then 2^k * 3^m = 6 * 4^k' * 9^m' == 1 * (-1)^k' * (-1)^m' (mod 5) == +- 1 (mod 5), so either 2^k * 3^m - 1 or 2^k * 3^m + 1 is divisible by 5. (End)
%e A394795 1 is in the sequence because 2^1*3^(1/1) = 6 is the average of some twin prime pair;
%e A394795 2 is in the sequence because 2^2*3^(2/2) = 6 is the average of some twin prime pair;
%e A394795 6 is in the sequence because 2^2*3^(6/2) = 108 is the average of some twin prime pair.
%t A394795 q[k_] := AnyTrue[Divisors[k], And @@ PrimeQ[2^# * 3^(k/#) + {-1, 1}] &]; Select[Range[1700], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Jun 08 2026 *)
%o A394795 (Magma) [k: k in [1..1700] | not #[d: d in Divisors(k) | IsPrime(2^d*3^(k div d)-1) and IsPrime(2^d*3^(k div d)+1)] eq 0];
%o A394795 (PARI) isok(k) = fordiv(k, d, my(x=2^d*3^(k/d)); if (ispseudoprime(x-1) && ispseudoprime(x+1), return(1))); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Jun 09 2026
%Y A394795 Cf. A014574, A161904, A027856, A386730, A385433.
